\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Aberration Type:}{\fs20\cf0  An aberration has a bizarre anatomy, strange abilities, an alien mindset, or any combination of the three.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Features: }{\fs20\cf0 An aberration has the following features.
\par \emdash d8 Hit Dice.
\par \emdash Base attack bonus equal to 3/4 total Hit Dice (as cleric).
\par \emdash Good Will saves.
\par \emdash Skill points equal to (2 + Int modifier, minimum 1) per Hit Die, with quadruple skill points for the first Hit Die.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 An aberration possesses the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash Darkvision out to 60 feet.
\par \emdash Proficient with its natural weapons. If generally humanoid in form, proficient with all simple weapons and any weapon it is described as using.
\par }\pard\plain \s15\ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs20\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\cf0 \emdash Proficient with whatever type of armor (light, medium, or heavy) it is described as wearing, as well as all lig
hter types. Aberrations not indicated as wearing armor are not proficient with armor. Aberrations are proficient with shields if they are proficient with any form of armor.
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\nowidctlpar\faauto\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\cf1\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\fs20\cf0 \emdash Aberrations eat, sleep, and breathe.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Ability Score Loss (Su):}{\fs20\cf0  Some attacks reduce the opponent\rquote s score in one or more abilities. This loss can be temporary (ability damage) or permanent (ability drain).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Ability Damage: }{\fs20\cf0 This attack damages an opponent\rquote s ability score. The creature\rquote s descriptive text gives the ability and the amount of d
amage. If an attack that causes ability damage scores a critical hit, it deals twice the indicated amount of damage (if the damage is expressed as a die range, roll two dice). Ability damage returns at the rate of 1 point per day for each affected ability
.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Ability Drain: }{\fs20\cf0 This effect permanently reduces a living opponent\rquote s ability score when the creature hits with a melee attack. The creature\rquote 
s descriptive text gives the ability and the amount drained. If an attack that causes ability drain scores a critical
 hit, it drains twice the indicated amount (if the damage is expressed as a die range, roll two dice). Unless otherwise specified in the creature\rquote 
s description, a draining creature gains 5 temporary hit points (10 on a critical hit) whenever it drains an ability score no matter how many points it drains. Temporary hit points gained in this fashion last for a maximum of 1 hour.
\par Some ability drain attacks allow a Fortitude save (DC 10 + 1/2 draining creature\rquote s racial HD + draining creature\rquote s Cha modifier; the exact DC is given in the creature\rquote 
s descriptive text). If no saving throw is mentioned, none is allowed.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Alternate Form (Su):}{\fs20\cf0  A creature with this special quality has the ability to assume one or more specific alternate forms. This ability works much like the }{\i\fs20\cf0 polymorph }{\fs20\cf0 
spell, except that the creature is limited to the forms specified, and does not regain any hit points for changing its form. Assuming an alternate form results in the following changes to the creature:
\par \emdash The creature retains the type and subtype of its original form. It gains the size of its new form.
\par \emdash The creature loses the natural weapons, natural armor, movement modes, and extraordinary special attacks of its original form.
\par \emdash The creature gains the natural weapons, natural armor, movement modes, and extraordinary special attacks of its new form.
\par \emdash The creature retains the special qualities of its original form. It does not gain any special qualities of its new form.
\par \emdash The creature retains the spell-like abilities and supernatural attacks of its old form (except for breath weapons and gaze attacks). It does not gain the spell-like abilities or supernatural attacks of its new form.
\par \emdash The creature gains the physical ability scores (Str, Dex, Con) of its new form. It retains the mental ability scores (Int, Wis, Cha) of its original form.
\par \emdash The creature retains its hit points and save bonuses, although its save modifiers may change due to a change in ability scores.
\par \emdash The creature retains any spellcasting ability it had in its original form, although it must be able to speak intelligibly to cast spells with verbal components and it must have humanlike hands to cast spells with somatic components.
\par \emdash The creature is effectively camouflaged as a creature of its new form, and it gains a +10 bonus on Disguise checks if it uses this ability to create a disguise.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Air Subtype:}{\fs20\cf0  This subtype usually is used for elementals and outsiders with a connection to the Elemental Plane Air. Air creatures always have fly speeds and usually have perfect maneuverability.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Angel Subtype:}{\fs20\cf0  Angels are a race of celestials, or good outsiders, native to the good-aligned Outer Planes.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 An angel possesses the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash Darkvision out to 60 feet and low-light vision.
\par \emdash Immunity to acid, cold, and petrification.
\par \emdash Resistance to electricity 10 and fire 10.
\par \emdash  +4 racial bonus on saves against poison.
\par \emdash Protective Aura (Su): Against attacks made or effects created by evil creatures, }{\i\fs20\cf0 t}{\fs20\cf0 
his ability provides a +4 deflection bonus to AC and a +4 resistance bonus on saving throws to anyone within 20 feet of the angel. Otherwise, it functions as a }{\i\fs20\cf0 magic circle against evil }{\fs20\cf0 effect and a }{\i\fs20\cf0 
lesser globe of invulnerability, }{\fs20\cf0 both with a radius of 20 feet (caster level equals angel\rquote s HD). (The defensive benefits from the circle are not included in an angel\rquote s statistics block.) 
\par \emdash Tongues (Su): All angels can speak with any creature that has a language, as though using a }{\i\fs20\cf0 tongues }{\fs20\cf0 spell (caster level equal to angel\rquote s Hit Dice). This ability is always active.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Animal Type:}{\fs20\cf0  An animal is a living, nonhuman creature, usually a vertebrate with no magical abilities and no innate capacity for language or culture.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Features: }{\fs20\cf0 An animal has the following features (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash d8 Hit Dice.
\par \emdash Base attack bonus equal to 3/4 total Hit Dice (as cleric).
\par \emdash Good Fortitude and Reflex saves (certain animals have different good saves).
\par \emdash Skill points equal to (2 + Int modifier, minimum 1) per Hit Die, with quadruple skill points for the first Hit Die.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 An animal possesses the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash Intelligence score of 1 or 2 (no creature with an Intelligence score of 3 or higher can be an animal).
\par \emdash Low-light vision.
\par \emdash Alignment: Always neutral.
\par \emdash Treasure: None.
\par \emdash Proficient with its natural weapons only. A noncombative herbivore uses its natural weapons as a secondary attack. Such attacks are made with a \endash 5 penalty on the creature\rquote s attack rolls, a
nd the animal receives only 1/2 its Strength modifier as a damage adjustment.
\par \emdash Proficient with no armor unless trained for war.
\par \emdash Animals eat, sleep, and breathe.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Aquatic Subtype:}{\fs20\cf0  These creatures always have swim speeds and thus can move in water without making Swim checks. An aquatic creature can breathe underwater. It cannot also breathe air unless it has the amphibious special quality. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Archon Subtype:}{\fs20\cf0  Archons are a race of celestials, or good outsiders, native to lawful good-aligned Outer Planes.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 An archon possesses the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash Darkvision out to 60 feet and low-light vision.
\par \emdash Aura of Menace (Su): A righteous aura surrounds archons that fight or get angry. Any hostile creature within a 20-
foot radius of an archon must succeed on a Will save to resist its effects. The save DC varies with the type of archon, is Charisma-based, and includes a +2 racial bonus. Those who fail take a \endash 
2 penalty on attacks, AC, and saves for 24 hours or until they successfully hit the archon that generated the aura. A creature that has resisted or broken the effect cannot be affected again by the same archon\rquote s aura for 24 hours.
\par \emdash Immunity to electricity and petrification.
\par \emdash  +4 racial bonus on saves against poison.
\par \emdash Magic Circle against Evil (Su): A magic circle against evil effect always surrounds an archon (caster level equals the archon\rquote s Hit Dice). (The defensive benefits from the circle are not included in an archon\rquote s statistics block.)

\par \emdash Teleport (Su): Archons can use greater teleport at will, as the spell (caster level 14th), except that the creature can transport only itself and up to 50 pounds of objects.
\par \emdash Tongues (Su): All archons can speak with any creature that has a language, as though using a }{\i\fs20\cf0 tongues }{\fs20\cf0 spell (caster level 14th). This ability is always active.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Augmented Subtype:}{\fs20\cf0  A creature receives this subtype whenever something happens to change its original type. Some creatures (those with an inherited template) are born with this subtype; others acqu
ire it when they take on an acquired template. The augmented subtype is always paired with the creature\rquote s original type. A creature with the augmented subtype usually has the traits of its current type, but the features of its original type.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Blindsense (Ex):}{\fs20\cf0 
 Using nonvisual senses, such as acute smell or hearing, a creature with blindsense notices things it cannot see. The creature usually does not need to make Spot or Listen checks to pinpoint the location of a creature within range of its blindsense abil
ity, provided that it has line of effect to that creature. Any opponent the creature cannot see still has total concealment against the creature with blindsense, and the creature still has the normal miss chance when attacking foes that have concealment. 
Visibility still affects the movement of a creature with blindsense. A creature with blindsense is still denied its Dexterity bonus to Armor Class against attacks from creatures it cannot see.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Blindsight (Ex):}{\fs20\cf0  This ability is similar to blindsense, but is 
far more discerning. Using nonvisual senses, such as sensitivity to vibrations, keen smell, acute hearing, or echolocation, a creature with blindsight maneuvers and fights as well as a sighted creature. Invisibility, darkness, and most kinds of concealmen
t are irrelevant, though the creature must have line of effect to a creature or object to discern that creature or object. The ability\rquote s range is specified in the creature\rquote 
s descriptive text. The creature usually does not need to make Spot or Listen checks 
to notice creatures within range of its blindsight ability. Unless noted otherwise, blindsight is continuous, and the creature need do nothing to use it. Some forms of blindsight, however, must be triggered as a free action. If so, this is noted in the cr
eature\rquote s description. If a creature must trigger its blindsight ability, the creature gains the benefits of blindsight only during its turn.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Breath Weapon (Su): }{\fs20\cf0 A breath weapon attack usually deals damage and is often based on some type of energy.
\par Such breath weapons allow a Reflex save for half damage (DC 10 + 1/2 breathing creature\rquote s racial HD + breathing creature\rquote s Con modifier; the exact DC is given in the creature\rquote 
s descriptive text). A creature is immune to its own breath weapon unless otherwise noted. Some breath weapons allow a Fortitude save or a Will save instead of a Reflex save.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Change Shape (Su):}{\fs20\cf0  A creature with this special quality has the ability to assume the appearance of a specific creature or type of creature (usually a humanoid), but ret
ains most of its own physical qualities. A creature cannot change shape to a form more than one size category smaller or larger than its original form. Changing shape results in the following changes to the creature:
\par \emdash The creature retains the type and subtype of its original form. It gains the size of its new form.
\par \emdash The creature loses the natural weapons, movement modes, and extraordinary special attacks of its original form.
\par \emdash The creature gains the natural weapons, movement modes, and extraordinary special attacks of its new form.
\par \emdash The creature retains all other special attacks and qualities of its original form, except for breath weapons and gaze attacks.
\par \emdash The creature retains the ability scores of its original form.
\par \emdash The creature retains its hit points and saves.
\par \emdash The creature retains any spellcasting ability it had in its original form, although it must be able to speak intelligibly to cast spells with verbal components and it must have humanlike hands to cast spells with somatic components.
\par \emdash The creature is effectively camouflaged as a creature of its new form, and gains a +10 bonus on Disguise checks if it uses this ability to create a disguise.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Chaotic Subtype: }{\fs20\cf0 A subtype usually applied only to outsiders native to the chaotic-aligned Outer Planes. Most
 creatures that have this subtype also have chaotic alignments; however, if their alignments change they still retain the subtype. Any effect that depends on alignment affects a creature with this subtype as if the creature has a chaotic alignment, no mat
t
er what its alignment actually is. The creature also suffers effects according to its actual alignment. A creature with the chaotic subtype overcomes damage reduction as if its natural weapons and any weapons it wields were chaotic-aligned (see Damage Red
uction, below).
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Cold Subtype: }{\fs20\cf0 A creature with the cold subtype has immunity to cold. It has vulnerability to fire, which means it takes half again as much (+50%) damage as normal from fire, regardless of whether a saving throw is allowed, or if the save is
 a success or failure. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Constrict (Ex):}{\fs20\cf0  A creature with this special attack can crush an opponent, dealing bludgeoning damage, after making a successful grapple check. The amount of damage is given in the creature\rquote s entry. If the creature also has the imp
roved grab ability it deals constriction damage in addition to damage dealt by the weapon used to grab.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Construct Type: }{\fs20\cf0 A construct is an animated object or artificially constructed creature.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Features: }{\fs20\cf0 A construct has the following features.
\par \emdash 10-sided Hit Dice.
\par \emdash Base attack bonus equal to 3/4 total Hit Dice (as cleric).
\par \emdash No good saving throws.
\par \emdash Skill points equal to (2 + Int modifier, minimum 1) per Hit Die, with quadruple skill points for the first Hit Die, if the construct has an Intelligence score. However, most constructs are mindless and gain no skill points or feats.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 A construct possesses the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash No Constitution score.
\par \emdash Low-light vision.
\par \emdash Darkvision out to 60 feet.
\par \emdash Immunity to all mind-affecting effects (charms, compulsions, phantasms, patterns, and morale effects).
\par \emdash Immunity to poison, sleep effects, paralysis, stunning, disease , death effects, and necromancy effects.
\par \emdash Cannot heal damage on their own, but often can be repaired by exposing them to a certain kind of effect (see the creature\rquote 
s description for details) or through the use of the Craft Construct feat. A construct with the fast healing special quality still benefits from that quality.
\par \emdash Not subject to critical hits, nonlethal damage, ability damage, ability drain, fatigue, exhaustion, or energy drain.
\par \emdash Immunity to any effect that requires a Fortitude save (unless the effect also works on objects, or is harmless).
\par \emdash Not at risk of death from massive damage. Immediately destroyed when reduced to 0 hit points or less.
\par \emdash Since it was never alive, a construct cannot be raised or resurrected.
\par \emdash Because its body is a mass of unliving matter, a construct is hard to destroy. It gains bonus hit points based on size, as shown on the following table.
