s description states otherwise. Damage reduction sufficient to reduce a swarm attack\rquote 
s damage to 0, being incorporeal, and other special abilities usually give a creature immunity (or at least resistance) to damage from a swarm. Some swarms also have acid, poison, blood drain, or other special attacks in addition to normal damage.
\par Swarms do not threaten creatures in their square, and do not make attacks of opportunity with their swarm attack. However, they distract foes whose squares they occupy, as described below.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Distraction (Ex): }{\fs20\cf0 Any living creature vulnerable to a swarm\rquote s damage that begins its turn with a swarm in its square is nauseated for 1 round; a Fortitude save (DC 10 + 1/2 swarm\rquote s HD + swarm\rquote 
s Con modifier; the exact DC is given in a swarm\rquote s description) negates the effect. Spellcasting or concentrating on spells within the area
 of a swarm requires a Concentration check (DC 20 + spell level). Using skills that involve patience and concentration requires a DC 20 Concentration check.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Telepathy (Su):}{\fs20\cf0  A creature with this ability can communicate telepathically with any other creature within a certain range (specified in the creature\rquote 
s entry, usually 100 feet) that has a language. It is possible to address multiple creatures at once telepathically, although maintaining a telepathic conversation with more than one creature at a time is
 just as difficult as simultaneously speaking and listening to multiple people at the same time.
\par Some creatures have a limited form of telepathy, while others have a more powerful form of the ability.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Trample (Ex):}{\fs20\cf0  As a full-round action, a creature with 
this special attack can move up to twice its speed and literally run over any opponents at least one size category smaller than itself. The creature merely has to move over the opponents in its path; any creature whose space is completely covered by the t
rampling creature\rquote s space is subject to the trample attack. If a target\rquote 
s space is larger than 5 feet, it is only considered trampled if the trampling creature moves over all the squares it occupies. If the trampling creature moves over only some of a target\rquote 
s space, the target can make an attack of opportunity against the trampling creature at a \endash 
4 penalty. A trampling creature that accidentally ends its movement in an illegal space returns to the last legal position it occupied, or the closest legal position, if there\rquote s a legal position that\rquote s closer.
\par A trample attack deals bludgeoning damage (the creature\rquote s slam damage + 1-1/2 times its Str modifier). The creature\rquote s descriptive text gives the exact amount.
\par Trampled opponents can attempt attacks of opportunity, but these take a \endash 4 penalty. If they do not make attacks of opportunity, trampled opponents can attempt Reflex saves to take half damage.
\par The save DC against a creature\rquote s trample attack is 10 + 1/2 creature\rquote s HD + creature\rquote s Str modifier (the exact DC is given in the creature\rquote 
s descriptive text). A trampling creature can only deal trampling damage to each target once per round, no matter how many times its movement takes it over a target creature.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Tremorsense (Ex): }{\fs20\cf0 A creature with tremorsense is sensi
tive to vibrations in the ground and can automatically pinpoint the location of anything that is in contact with the ground. Aquatic creatures with tremorsense can also sense the location of creatures moving through water. The ability\rquote 
s range is specified in the creature\rquote s descriptive text.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Treasure:}{\fs20\cf0  This entry in a monster description describes how much wealth a creature owns. In most cases, a creature keeps valuables in its home or lair and has no treasure with it when it travels. Intelligent creatures t
hat own useful, portable treasure (such as magic items) tend to carry and use these, leaving bulky items at home. Treasure can include coins, goods, and items. Creatures can have varying amounts of each, as follows.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Standard: }{\fs20\cf0 Refer to the treasure tables}{\i\fs20\cf0  }{\fs20\cf0 and roll d% once for each type of treasure (Coins, Goods, Items) on the Level section of the table that corresponds to the creature\rquote 
s Challenge Rating (for groups of creatures, use the Encounter Level for the encounter instead). Some creatures have double, triple, or even quadruple standard treasure; in these cases, roll for each type of treasure two, three, or four times.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 None: }{\fs20\cf0 The creature collects no treasure of its own.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Nonstandard: }{\fs20\cf0 Some creatures have quirks or habits that affect the types of treasure they collect. These creatures use the same
\par treasure tables, but with special adjustments.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Fractional Coins: }{\fs20\cf0 Roll on the Coins column in the section corresponding to the creature\rquote s Challenge Rating, but divide the result as indicated.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 % Goods or Items: }{\fs20\cf0 The creature has goods or items only some of the time. Before checking for goods or items, roll d% against the given percentage. On a success, make a normal roll on the appropriate Goods or
 Items column (which may still result in no goods or items).
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Double Goods or Items: }{\fs20\cf0 Roll twice on the appropriate Goods or Items column.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Parenthetical Notes: }{\fs20\cf0 Some entries for goods or items include notes that limit the types of treasure a creature collects.
\par When a note includes the word \'93no,\'94 it means the creature does not collect or cannot keep that thing. If a random roll generates such a result, treat the result as \'93none\'94 instead. 
\par When a note includes the word \'93only,\'94 the creature goes out of its way to collect treasure of the indicated type. Treat all results from that column as the indicated type of treasure.
\par It\rquote s sometimes necessary to reroll until the right sort of item appears. 
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Turn Resistance (Ex): }{\fs20\cf0 A creature with this special quality (usually an undead) is less easily affected by clerics or paladins. When resolving a turn, rebuke, command, or bolster attempt, add the indicated number to the creature\rquote 
s Hit Dice total.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Undead Type:}{\fs20\cf0  Undead are once-living creatures animated by spiritual or supernatural forces.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Features: }{\fs20\cf0 An undead creature has the following features.
\par \emdash 12-sided Hit Dice.
\par \emdash Base attack bonus equal to 1/2 total Hit Dice (as wizard).
\par \emdash Good Will saves.
\par \emdash Skill points equal to (4 + Int modifier, minimum 1) per Hit Die, with quadruple skill points for the first Hit Die, if the undead creature has an Intelligence score. However, many undead are mindless and gain no skill points or feats.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 An undead creature possesses the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash No Constitution score.
\par \emdash Darkvision out to 60 feet.
\par \emdash Immunity to all mind-affecting effects (charms, compulsions, phantasms, patterns, and morale effects).
\par \emdash Immunity to poison, sleep effects, paralysis, stunning, disease, and death effects.
\par \emdash Not subject to critical hits, nonlethal damage, ability drain, or energy drain. Immune to damage to its physical ability scores (Strength, Dexterity, and Constitution), as well as to fatigue and exhaustion effects.
\par \emdash Cannot heal damage on its own if it has no Intelligence score, although it can be healed. Negative energy (such as an }{\i\fs20\cf0 inflict }{\fs20\cf0 
spell) can heal undead creatures. The fast healing special quality works regardless of the creature\rquote s Intelligence score.
\par \emdash Immunity to any effect that requires a Fortitude save (unless the effect also works on objects or is harmless).
\par \emdash Uses its Charisma modifier for Concentration checks.
\par \emdash Not at risk of death from massive damage, but when reduced to 0 hit points or less, it is immediately destroyed.
\par \emdash Not affected by }{\i\fs20\cf0 raise dead }{\fs20\cf0 and }{\i\fs20\cf0 reincarnate }{\fs20\cf0 spells or abilities. }{\i\fs20\cf0 Resurrection }{\fs20\cf0 and }{\i\fs20\cf0 true resurrection }{\fs20\cf0 
can affect undead creatures. These spells turn undead creatures back into the living creatures they were before becoming undead.
\par \emdash Proficient with its natural weapons, all simple weapons, and any weapons mentioned in its entry.
\par \emdash Proficient with whatever type of armor (light, medium, or heavy) it is described as wearing, as well as all lighter types. Undead not indicated as wearing arm
or are not proficient with armor. Undead are proficient with shields if they are proficient with any form of armor.
\par \emdash Undead do not breathe, eat, or sleep.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 
\par Vermin Type:}{\fs20\cf0  This type includes insects, arachnids, other arthropods, worms, and similar invertebrates.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Features: }{\fs20\cf0 Vermin have the following features.
\par \emdash 8-sided Hit Dice.
\par \emdash Base attack bonus equal to 3/4 total Hit Dice (as cleric).
\par \emdash Good Fortitude saves.
\par \emdash Skill points equal to (2 + Int modifier, minimum 1) per Hit Die, with quadruple skill points for the first Hit Die, if the vermin has an Intelligence score. However, most vermin are mindless and gain no skill points or feats.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Traits: }{\fs20\cf0 Vermin possess the following traits (unless otherwise noted in a creature\rquote s entry).
\par \emdash Mindless: No Intelligence score, and immunity to all mind-affecting effects (charms, compulsions, phantasms, patterns, and morale effects).
\par \emdash Darkvision out to 60 feet.
\par \emdash Proficient with their natural weapons only.
\par \emdash Proficient with no armor.
